# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: formal-equivalence-checking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In computer science, a **binary decision diagram** (**BDD**) or **branching program** is a data structure that is used to represent a Boolean function.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] On a more abstract level, BDDs can be considered as a compressed representation of sets or relations.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Unlike other compressed representations, operations are performed directly on the compressed representation, i.e. without decompression.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Similar data structures include negation normal form (NNF), Zhegalkin polynomials, and propositional directed acyclic graphs (PDAG).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] A Boolean function can be represented as a rooted, directed, acyclic graph, which consists of several (decision) nodes and two terminal nodes.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The two terminal nodes are labeled 0 (FALSE) and 1 (TRUE).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Each (decision) node u is labeled by a Boolean variable $x_{i}$ and has two child nodes called low child and high child.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The edge from node u to a low (or high) child represents an assignment of the value FALSE (or TRUE, respectively) to variable $x_{i}$ .
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Such a **BDD** is called 'ordered' if different variables appear in the same order on all paths from the root.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In popular usage, the term **BDD** almost always refers to **Reduced Ordered Binary Decision Diagram** (**ROBDD** in the literature, used when the ordering and reduction aspects need to be emphasized).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The advantage of an ROBDD is that it is canonical (unique up to isomorphism) for a particular function and variable order.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This property makes it useful in functional equivalence checking and other operations like functional technology mapping.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] A path from the root node to the 1-terminal represents a (possibly partial) variable assignment for which the represented Boolean function is true.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] As the path descends to a low (or high) child from a node, then that node's variable is assigned to 0 (respectively 1).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The left figure below shows a binary decision *tree* (the reduction rules are not applied), and a truth table, each representing the function $f(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})$ .
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In the tree on the left, the value of the function can be determined for a given variable assignment by following a path down the graph to a terminal.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In the figures below, dotted lines represent edges to a low child, while solid lines represent edges to a high child.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Therefore, to find $f(0,1,1)$ , begin at x1, traverse down the dotted line to x2 (since x1 has an assignment to 0), then down two solid lines (since x2 and x3 each have an assignment to one).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This leads to the terminal 1, which is the value of $f(0,1,1)$ .
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The binary decision *tree* of the left figure can be transformed into a binary decision *diagram* by maximally reducing it according to the two reduction rules.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The resulting **BDD** is shown in the right figure.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] An ROBDD can be represented even more compactly, using complemented edges, also known as *complement links*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The resulting BDD is sometimes known as a *typed BDD* or *signed BDD*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Complemented edges are formed by annotating low edges as complemented or not.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] If an edge is complemented, then it refers to the negation of the Boolean function that corresponds to the node that the edge points to (the Boolean function represented by the BDD with root that node).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] High edges are not complemented, in order to ensure that the resulting BDD representation is a canonical form.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In this representation, BDDs have a single leaf node, for reasons explained below.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] A reference to a BDD in this representation is a (possibly complemented) "edge" that points to the root of the BDD.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This is in contrast to a reference to a BDD in the representation without use of complemented edges, which is the root node of the BDD.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The reason why a reference in this representation needs to be an edge is that for each Boolean function, the function and its negation are represented by an edge to the root of a BDD, and a complemented edge to the root of the same BDD.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This is why negation takes constant time.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] It also explains why a single leaf node suffices: FALSE is represented by a complemented edge that points to the leaf node, and TRUE is represented by an ordinary edge (i.e., not complemented) that points to the leaf node.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] For example, assume that a Boolean function is represented with a BDD represented using complemented edges.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] While following this path, we count how many complemented edges we have traversed.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] An example diagram of a BDD in this representation is shown on the right, and represents the same Boolean expression as shown in diagrams above, i.e., $(\neg x_{1}\wedge \neg x_{2}\wedge \neg x_{3})\vee (x_{1}\wedge x_{2})\vee (x_{2}\wedge x_{3})$ .
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Low edges are dashed, high edges solid, and complemented edges are signified by a circle at their source.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The node with the @ symbol represents the reference to the BDD, i.e., the reference edge is the edge that starts from this node.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The basic idea from which the data structure was created is the Shannon expansion.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] A switching function is split into two sub-functions (cofactors) by assigning one variable (cf.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] If such a sub-function is considered as a sub-tree, it can be represented by a *binary decision tree*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Binary decision diagrams (BDDs) were introduced by C.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Lee, and further studied and made known by Sheldon B.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Independently of these authors, a BDD under the name "canonical bracket form" was realized Yu.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Mamrukov in a CAD for analysis of speed-independent circuits.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The full potential for efficient algorithms based on the data structure was investigated by Randal Bryant at Carnegie Mellon University: his key extensions were to use a fixed variable ordering (for canonical representation) and shared sub-graphs (for compression).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Applying these two concepts results in an efficient data structure and algorithms for the representation of sets and relations.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] By extending the sharing to several BDDs, i.e. one sub-graph is used by several BDDs, the data structure *Shared Reduced Ordered Binary Decision Diagram* is defined.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The notion of a BDD is now generally used to refer to that particular data structure.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In his video lecture *Fun With Binary Decision Diagrams (BDDs)*, Donald Knuth calls BDDs "one of the only really fundamental data structures that came out in the last twenty-five years" and mentions that Bryant's 1986 paper was for some time one of the most-cited papers in computer science.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Adnan Darwiche and his collaborators have shown that BDDs are one of several normal forms for Boolean functions, each induced by a different combination of requirements.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Another important normal form identified by Darwiche is decomposable negation normal form or DNNF.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] BDDs are extensively used in CAD software to synthesize circuits (logic synthesis) and in formal verification and network verification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] There are several lesser known applications of BDD, including fault tree analysis, Bayesian reasoning, product configuration, and private information retrieval.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Every arbitrary BDD (even if it is not reduced or ordered) can be directly implemented in hardware by replacing each node with a 2 to 1 multiplexer; each multiplexer can be directly implemented by a 4-LUT in a FPGA.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] It is not so simple to convert from an arbitrary network of logic gates to a BDD (unlike the and-inverter graph).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] BDDs have been applied in efficient Datalog interpreters.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The size of the BDD is determined both by the function being represented and by the chosen ordering of the variables.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] There exist Boolean functions $f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ for which depending upon the ordering of the variables we would end up getting a graph whose number of nodes would be linear (in *n*) at best and exponential at worst (e.g., a ripple carry adder).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] It is of crucial importance to care about variable ordering when applying this data structure in practice.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] The problem of finding the best variable ordering is NP-hard.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] For any constant *c* > 1 it is even NP-hard to compute a variable ordering resulting in an OBDD with a size that is at most *c* times larger than an optimal one.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] However, there exist efficient heuristics to tackle the problem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] There are functions for which the graph size is always exponential—independent of variable ordering.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This holds e.g. for the multiplication function.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] In fact, the function computing the middle bit of the product of two n -bit numbers does not have an OBDD smaller than $2^{\lfloor n/2\rfloor }/61-4$ vertices.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] (If the multiplication function had polynomial-size OBDDs, it would show that integer factorization is in P/poly, which is not known to be true.) Another notorious example is the hidden weight bit function, regarded as the simplest function with an exponential-sized BDD.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] However, repeating these operations several times, for example forming the conjunction or disjunction of a set of BDDs, may in the worst case result in an exponentially big BDD.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] This is because any of the preceding operations for two BDDs may result in a BDD with a size proportional to the product of the BDDs' sizes, and consequently for several BDDs the size may be exponential in the number of operations.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Variable ordering needs to be considered afresh; what may be a good ordering for (some of) the set of BDDs may not be a good ordering for the result of the operation.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Also, since constructing the BDD of a Boolean function solves the NP-complete Boolean satisfiability problem and the co-NP-complete tautology problem, constructing the BDD can take exponential time in the size of the Boolean formula even when the resulting BDD is small.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Computing existential abstraction over multiple variables of reduced BDDs is NP-complete.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] Model-counting, counting the number of satisfying assignments of a Boolean formula, can be done in polynomial time for BDDs.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/binary-decision-diagram] For general propositional formulas the problem is ♯P-complete and the best known algorithms require an exponential time in the worst case.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In logic and computer science, the **Boolean satisfiability problem** (sometimes called **propositional satisfiability problem** and abbreviated **SATISFIABILITY**, **SAT** or **B-SAT**) asks whether there exists an interpretation that satisfies a given Boolean formula.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In other words, it asks whether the formula's variables can be consistently replaced by the values TRUE or FALSE to make the formula evaluate to TRUE.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If this is the case, the formula is called *satisfiable*, else *unsatisfiable*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, the formula "*a* AND NOT *b*" is satisfiable because one can find the values *a* = TRUE and *b* = FALSE, which make (*a* AND NOT *b*) = TRUE.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, "*a* AND NOT *a*" is unsatisfiable.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is the first problem that was proven to be NP-complete—this is the Cook–Levin theorem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This means that all problems in the complexity class NP, which includes a wide range of natural decision and optimization problems, are at most as difficult to solve as SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is no known algorithm that efficiently solves each SAT problem (where "efficiently" means "deterministically in polynomial time").
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although such an algorithm is generally believed not to exist, this belief has not been proven or disproven mathematically.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Resolving the question of whether SAT has a polynomial-time algorithm would settle the P versus NP problem - one of the most important open problems in the theory of computing.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Nevertheless, heuristic SAT-algorithms are able to solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and formulas consisting of millions of symbols, which is sufficient for many practical SAT problems occurring in artificial intelligence, circuit design, and automatic theorem proving.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *propositional logic formula*, also called *Boolean expression*, is built from variables, operators AND (conjunction, also denoted by ∧), OR (disjunction, ∨), NOT (negation, ¬), and parentheses.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is said to be *satisfiable* if it can be made TRUE by assigning appropriate logical values (i.e.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The *Boolean satisfiability problem* (SAT) is, given a formula, to check whether it is satisfiable.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This decision problem is of central importance in many areas of computer science, including theoretical computer science, complexity theory, algorithmics, cryptography and artificial intelligence.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *literal* is either a variable (in which case it is called a *positive literal*) or the negation of a variable (called a *negative literal*).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A *clause* is a disjunction of literals (or a single literal).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A clause is called a *Horn clause* if it contains at most one positive literal.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A formula is in *conjunctive normal form* (CNF) if it is a conjunction of clauses (or a single clause).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, *x*1 is a positive literal, ¬*x*2 is a negative literal, and *x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2 is a clause.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula (*x*1 ∨ ¬*x*2) ∧ (¬*x*1 ∨ *x*2 ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬*x*1 is in conjunctive normal form; its first and third clauses are Horn clauses, but its second clause is not.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula is satisfiable, by choosing *x*1 = FALSE, *x*2 = FALSE, and *x*3 arbitrarily, since (FALSE ∨ ¬FALSE) ∧ (¬FALSE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ ¬FALSE evaluates to (FALSE ∨ TRUE) ∧ (TRUE ∨ FALSE ∨ *x*3) ∧ TRUE, and in turn to TRUE ∧ TRUE ∧ TRUE (i.e. to TRUE).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In contrast, the CNF formula *a* ∧ ¬*a*, consisting of two clauses of one literal, is unsatisfiable, since for *a*=TRUE or *a*=FALSE it evaluates to TRUE ∧ ¬TRUE (i.e., FALSE) or FALSE ∧ ¬FALSE (i.e., again FALSE), respectively.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For some versions of the SAT problem, it is useful to define the notion of a *generalized conjunctive normal form* formula, viz. as a conjunction of arbitrarily many *generalized clauses*, the latter being of the form *R*(*l*1,...,*l**n*) for some Boolean function *R* and (ordinary) literals *l**i*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different sets of allowed Boolean functions lead to different problem versions.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This formula is used below, with *R* being the ternary operator that is TRUE just when exactly one of its arguments is.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Using the laws of Boolean algebra, every propositional logic formula can be transformed into an equivalent conjunctive normal form, which may, however, be exponentially longer.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] while the former is a disjunction of *n* conjunctions of 2 variables, the latter consists of 2*n* clauses of *n* variables.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, with use of the Tseytin transformation, we may find an equisatisfiable conjunctive normal form formula with length linear in the size of the original propositional logic formula.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT was the first problem known to be NP-complete, as proved by Stephen Cook at the University of Toronto in 1971 and independently by Leonid Levin at the Russian Academy of Sciences in 1973.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Until that time, the concept of an NP-complete problem did not even exist.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The proof shows how every decision problem in the complexity class NP can be reduced to the SAT problem for CNF formulas, sometimes called **CNFSAT**.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A useful property of Cook's reduction is that it preserves the number of accepting answers.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For example, deciding whether a given graph has a 3-coloring is another problem in NP; if a graph has 17 valid 3-colorings, then the SAT formula produced by the Cook–Levin reduction will have 17 satisfying assignments.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] NP-completeness only refers to the run-time of the worst case instances.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Many of the instances that occur in practical applications can be solved much more quickly.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Like the satisfiability problem for arbitrary formulas, determining the satisfiability of a formula in conjunctive normal form where each clause is limited to at most three literals is NP-complete also; this problem is called **3-SAT**, **3CNFSAT**, or **3-satisfiability**.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] where *x*2, ⋯ , *x**n*−2 are fresh variables not occurring elsewhere.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Although the two formulas are not logically equivalent, they are equisatisfiable.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The formula resulting from transforming all clauses is at most 3 times as long as its original; that is, the length growth is polynomial.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-SAT is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems, and it is used as a starting point for proving that other problems are also NP-hard.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is done by polynomial-time reduction from 3-SAT to the other problem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of a problem where this method has been used is the clique problem: given a CNF formula consisting of *c* clauses, the corresponding graph consists of a vertex for each literal, and an edge between each two non-contradicting literals from different clauses; see the picture.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The graph has a *c*-clique if and only if the formula is satisfiable.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] There is a simple randomized algorithm due to Schöning (1999) that runs in time (4/3)*n* where *n* is the number of variables in the 3-SAT proposition, and succeeds with high probability to correctly decide 3-SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The exponential time hypothesis asserts that no algorithm can solve 3-SAT (or indeed *k*-SAT for any *k* > 2) in exp(*o*(*n*)) time (that is, fundamentally faster than exponential in *n*).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Selman, Mitchell, and Levesque (1996) give empirical data on the difficulty of randomly generated 3-SAT formulas, depending on their size parameters.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Difficulty is measured in number recursive calls made by a DPLL algorithm.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] They identified a phase transition region from almost-certainly-satisfiable to almost-certainly-unsatisfiable formulas at the clauses-to-variables ratio at about 4.26.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] 3-satisfiability can be generalized to **k-satisfiability** (**k-SAT**, also **k-CNF-SAT**), when formulas in CNF are considered with each clause containing up to k literals.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] However, since for any *k* ≥ 3, this problem can neither be easier than 3-SAT nor harder than SAT, and the latter two are NP-complete, so must be k-SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Some authors restrict k-SAT to CNF formulas with **exactly k literals**.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This does not lead to a different complexity class either, as each clause with fewer than k literals can be padded with repeated copies of the same literals.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Satisfiability and solution space geometry of k-SAT problems with randomly generated clauses have been investigated statistically.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As a function of the clause-to-variable ratio (also known as the density), the model exhibits various phase transitions regarding satisfiability and solution space geometry.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] For satisfiability, there exists a sharp threshold such that with high probability a solution exists if and only if the density remains below this threshold.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Well below the satisfiability threshold, the solution space also undergoes a geometric phase transition, namely that it shatters into exponentially many, well-separated clusters.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The onset of this phase transition coincides with the known algorithmic threshold, suggesting a link between geometry and algorithmic intractability.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Conjunctive normal form (in particular with 3 literals per clause) is often considered the canonical representation for SAT formulas.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] As shown above, the general SAT problem reduces to 3-SAT, the problem of determining satisfiability for formulas in this form.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A 3-SAT formula is *Linear SAT* (*LSAT*) if each clause (viewed as a set of literals) intersects at most one other clause, and, moreover, if two clauses intersect, then they have exactly one literal in common.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An LSAT formula can be depicted as a set of disjoint semi-closed intervals on a line.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Deciding whether an LSAT formula is satisfiable is NP-complete.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is easier if the number of literals in a clause is limited to at most 2, in which case the problem is called **2-SAT**.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem can be solved in polynomial time, and in fact is complete for the complexity class NL.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If additionally all OR operations in literals are changed to XOR operations, then the result is called **exclusive-or 2-satisfiability**, which is a problem complete for the complexity class SL = L.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The problem of deciding the satisfiability of a given conjunction of Horn clauses is called **Horn-satisfiability**, or **HORN-SAT**.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be solved in polynomial time by a single step of the unit propagation algorithm, which produces the single minimal model of the set of Horn clauses (w.r.t. the set of literals assigned to TRUE).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It can be seen as P's version of the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Also, deciding the truth of quantified Horn formulas can be done in polynomial time.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Horn clauses are of interest because they are able to express implication of one variable from a set of other variables.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A generalization of the class of Horn formulas is that of renameable-Horn formulae, which is the set of formulas that can be placed in Horn form by replacing some variables with their respective negation.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Checking the existence of such a replacement can be done in linear time; therefore, the satisfiability of such formulae is in P as it can be solved by first performing this replacement and then checking the satisfiability of the resulting Horn formula.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT is trivial if the formulas are restricted to those in **disjunctive normal form**, that is, they are a disjunction of conjunctions of literals.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such a formula is indeed satisfiable if and only if at least one of its conjunctions is satisfiable, and a conjunction is satisfiable if and only if it does not contain both *x* and NOT *x* for some variable *x*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Furthermore, if they are restricted to being in **full disjunctive normal form**, in which every variable appears exactly once in every conjunction, they can be checked in constant time (each conjunction represents one satisfying assignment).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] But it can take exponential time and space to convert a general SAT problem to disjunctive normal form; to obtain an example, exchange "∧" and "∨" in the above exponential blow-up example for conjunctive normal forms.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another NP-complete variant of the 3-satisfiability problem is the **one-in-three 3-SAT** (also known variously as **1-in-3-SAT** and **exactly-1 3-SAT**).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine whether there exists a truth assignment to the variables so that each clause has *exactly* one TRUE literal (and thus exactly two FALSE literals).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another variant is the **not-all-equal 3-satisfiability** problem (also called **NAE3SAT**).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Given a conjunctive normal form with three literals per clause, the problem is to determine if an assignment to the variables exists such that in no clause all three literals have the same truth value.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This problem is NP-complete, too, even if no negation symbols are admitted, by Schaefer's dichotomy theorem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Another special case is the class of problems where each clause contains XOR (i.e. exclusive or) rather than (plain) OR operators.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] This is in P, since an XOR-SAT formula can also be viewed as a system of linear equations mod 2, and can be solved in cubic time by Gaussian elimination.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The restrictions above (CNF, 2CNF, 3CNF, Horn, XOR-SAT) bound the considered formulae to be conjunctions of subformulas; each restriction states a specific form for all subformulas: for example, only binary clauses can be subformulas in 2CNF.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Schaefer's dichotomy theorem states that, for any restriction to Boolean functions that can be used to form these subformulas, the corresponding satisfiability problem is in P or NP-complete.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The membership in P of the satisfiability of 2CNF, Horn, and XOR-SAT formulae are special cases of this theorem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The following table summarizes some common variants of SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An extension that has gained significant popularity since 2003 is **satisfiability modulo theories** (**SMT**) that can enrich CNF formulas with linear constraints, arrays, all-different constraints, uninterpreted functions, etc.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Such extensions typically remain NP-complete, but very efficient solvers are now available that can handle many such kinds of constraints.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] The satisfiability problem becomes more difficult if both "for all" (∀) and "there exists" (∃) quantifiers are allowed to bind the Boolean variables.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] An example of such an expression would be ∀*x* ∀*y* ∃*z* (*x* ∨ *y* ∨ *z*) ∧ (¬*x* ∨ ¬*y* ∨ ¬*z*); it is valid, since for all values of *x* and *y*, an appropriate value of *z* can be found, viz.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] *z*=TRUE if both *x* and *y* are FALSE, and *z*=FALSE else.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT itself (tacitly) uses only ∃ quantifiers.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If only ∀ quantifiers are allowed instead, the so-called **tautology problem** is obtained, which is co-NP-complete.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If any number of both quantifiers are allowed, the problem is called the **quantified Boolean formula problem** (**QBF**), which can be shown to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] It is widely believed that PSPACE-complete problems are strictly harder than any problem in NP, although this has not yet been proved.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Ordinary SAT asks if there is at least one variable assignment that makes the formula true.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Other generalizations include satisfiability for first- and second-order logic, constraint satisfaction problems, 0-1 integer programming.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] While SAT is a decision problem, the search problem of finding a satisfying assignment reduces to SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] That is, each algorithm which correctly answers whether an instance of SAT is solvable can be used to find a satisfying assignment.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] First, the question is asked on the given formula Φ.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "no", the formula is unsatisfiable.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Otherwise, the question is asked on the partly instantiated formula Φ{*x*1=TRUE}, that is, Φ with the first variable *x*1 replaced by TRUE, and simplified accordingly.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] If the answer is "yes", then *x*1=TRUE, otherwise *x*1=FALSE.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Values of other variables can be found subsequently in the same way.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In total, *n*+1 runs of the algorithm are required, where *n* is the number of distinct variables in Φ.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Since the SAT problem is NP-complete, only algorithms with exponential worst-case complexity are known for it.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] In spite of this, efficient and scalable algorithms for SAT were developed during the 2000s and have contributed to dramatic advances in the ability to automatically solve problem instances involving tens of thousands of variables and millions of constraints (i.e. clauses).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Examples of such problems in electronic design automation (EDA) include formal equivalence checking, model checking, formal verification of pipelined microprocessors, automatic test pattern generation, routing of FPGAs, planning, and scheduling problems, and so on.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] A SAT-solving engine is also considered to be an essential component in the electronic design automation toolbox.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Major techniques used by modern SAT solvers include the Davis–Putnam–Logemann–Loveland algorithm (or DPLL), conflict-driven clause learning (CDCL), and stochastic local search algorithms such as WalkSAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Almost all SAT solvers include time-outs, so they will terminate in reasonable time even if they cannot find a solution.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Different SAT solvers will find different instances easy or hard, and some excel at proving unsatisfiability, and others at finding solutions.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Recent attempts have been made to learn an instance's satisfiability using deep learning techniques.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] SAT solvers are developed and compared in SAT-solving contests.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Modern SAT solvers are also having significant impact on the fields of software verification, constraint solving in artificial intelligence, and operations research, among others.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/boolean-satisfiability-problem] Earlier runtime guarantees are shown in the diagram.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] A **counterexample** is a specific example that contradicts a claim, hypothesis, or generalization.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In logic a counterexample disproves a universally stated claim, and does so rigorously in the fields of mathematics and philosophy.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In mathematics, counterexamples are often used to prove the boundaries of possible theorems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] By using counterexamples to show that certain conjectures are false, mathematical researchers can then avoid going down blind alleys and learn to modify conjectures to produce provable theorems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] It is sometimes said that mathematical development consists primarily in finding (and proving) theorems and counterexamples.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Suppose that a mathematician is studying geometry and shapes, and she wishes to prove certain theorems about them.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] She conjectures that "All rectangles are squares", and she is interested in knowing whether this statement is true or false.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In this case, she can either attempt to prove the truth of the statement using deductive reasoning, or she can attempt to find a counterexample of the statement if she suspects it to be false.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In the latter case, a counterexample would be a rectangle that is not a square, such as a rectangle with two sides of length 5 and two sides of length 7.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] However, despite having found rectangles that were not squares, all the rectangles she did find had four sides.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] She then makes the new conjecture "All rectangles have four sides".
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] This is logically weaker than her original conjecture, since every square has four sides, but not every four-sided shape is a square.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] The above example explained — in a simplified way — how a mathematician might weaken her conjecture in the face of counterexamples, but counterexamples can also be used to demonstrate the necessity of certain assumptions and hypothesis.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] For example, suppose that after a while, the mathematician above settled on the new conjecture "All shapes that are rectangles and have four sides of equal length are squares".
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] This conjecture has two parts to the hypothesis: the shape must be 'a rectangle' and must have 'four sides of equal length'.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] The mathematician then would like to know if she can remove either assumption, and still maintain the truth of her conjecture.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] "All shapes that have four sides of equal length are squares".
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] A counterexample to (1) was already given above, and a counterexample to (2) is a non-square rhombus.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Thus, the mathematician now knows that each assumption by itself is insufficient.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] A counterexample to the statement "all prime numbers are odd numbers" is the number 2, as it is a prime number but is not an odd number.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Neither of the numbers 7 or 10 is a counterexample, as neither of them are enough to contradict the statement.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In this example, 2 is in fact the only possible counterexample to the statement, even though that alone is enough to contradict the statement.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In a similar manner, the statement "All natural numbers are either prime or composite" has the number 1 as a counterexample, as 1 is neither prime nor composite.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Euler's sum of powers conjecture was disproved by counterexample.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] It asserted that at least *n* *n*th powers were necessary to sum to another *n*th power.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] This conjecture was disproved in 1966, with a counterexample involving *n* = 5; other *n* = 5 counterexamples are now known, as well as some *n* = 4 counterexamples.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Witsenhausen's counterexample shows that it is not always true (for control problems) that a quadratic loss function and a linear equation of evolution of the state variable imply optimal control laws that are linear.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] All Euclidean plane isometries are mappings that preserve area, but the converse is false as shown by counterexamples shear mapping and squeeze mapping.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Other examples include the disproofs of the Seifert conjecture, the Pólya conjecture, the conjecture of Hilbert's fourteenth problem, Tait's conjecture, and the Ganea conjecture.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] In philosophy, counterexamples are usually used to argue that a certain philosophical position is wrong by showing that it does not apply in certain cases.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Alternatively, the first philosopher can modify their claim so that the counterexample no longer applies; this is analogous to when a mathematician modifies a conjecture because of a counterexample.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] For example, in Plato's *Gorgias*, Callicles argues that those who are physically stronger or more capable are naturally entitled to rule over weaker people.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Socrates responds by proposing that the sheer number of ordinary people, by virtue of their combined strength, could be considered "stronger" than the aristocratic few even though the masses are *prima facie* of worse character.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] This presents a counterexample Callicles' claim, by shifting the notion of strength from individual superiority to collective power.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Callicles' argument therefore fails under this alternative interpretation, unless he revises his claim.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] Callicles might challenge Socrates' counterexample, arguing perhaps that the common rabble really are better than the nobles, or that even in their large numbers, they still are not stronger.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] But if Callicles accepts the counterexample, then he must either withdraw his claim, or modify it so that the counterexample no longer applies.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] For example, he might modify his claim to refer only to individual persons, requiring him to think of the common people as a collection of individuals rather than as a mob.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/counterexample] As it happens, he modifies his claim to say "wiser" instead of "stronger", arguing that no amount of numerical superiority can make people wiser.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] In general, there is a wide range of possible definitions of functional equivalence covering comparisons between different levels of abstraction and varying granularity of timing details.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] The register transfer level (RTL) behavior of a digital chip is usually described with a hardware description language, such as Verilog or VHDL.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] This description is the golden reference model that describes in detail which operations will be executed during which clock cycle and by which pieces of hardware.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Once the logic designers, by simulations and other verification methods, have verified register transfer description, the design is usually converted into a netlist by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Equivalence is not to be confused with functional correctness, which must be determined by functional verification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] The initial netlist will usually undergo a number of transformations such as optimization, addition of Design For Test (DFT) structures, etc., before it is used as the basis for the placement of the logic elements into a physical layout.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Contemporary physical design software will occasionally also make significant modifications (such as replacing logic elements with equivalent similar elements that have a higher or lower drive strength and/or area) to the netlist.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Throughout every step of a very complex, multi-step procedure, the original functionality and the behavior described by the original code must be maintained.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] When the final tape-out is made of a digital chip, many different EDA programs and possibly some manual edits will have altered the netlist.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] In theory, a logic synthesis tool guarantees that the first netlist is logically equivalent to the RTL source code.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] All the programs later in the process that make changes to the netlist also, in theory, ensure that these changes are logically equivalent to a previous version.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] In practice, programs have bugs and it would be a major risk to assume that all steps from RTL through the final tape-out netlist have been performed without error.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Also, in real life, it is common for designers to make manual changes to a netlist, commonly known as Engineering Change Orders, or ECOs, thereby introducing a major additional error factor.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Therefore, instead of blindly assuming that no mistakes were made, a verification step is needed to check the logical equivalence of the final version of the netlist to the original description of the design (golden reference model).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Historically, one way to check the equivalence was to re-simulate, using the final netlist, the test cases that were developed for verifying the correctness of the RTL.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] This process is called gate level logic simulation.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] However, the problem with this is that the quality of the check is only as good as the quality of the test cases.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Also, gate-level simulations are notoriously slow to execute, which is a major problem as the size of digital designs continues to grow exponentially.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] An alternative way to solve this is to formally prove that the RTL code and the netlist synthesized from it have exactly the same behavior in all (relevant) cases.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] This process is called formal equivalence checking and is a problem that is studied under the broader area of formal verification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] A formal equivalence check can be performed between any two representations of a design: RTL <> netlist, netlist <> netlist or RTL <> RTL, though the latter is rare compared to the first two.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-equivalence-checking] Typically, a formal equivalence checking tool will also indicate with great precision at which point there exists a difference between two representations.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] In the context of hardware and software systems, **formal verification** is the act of proving or disproving the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Formal verification is a key incentive for formal specification of systems, and is at the core of formal methods.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] It represents an important dimension of analysis and verification in electronic design automation and is one approach to software verification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The use of formal verification enables the highest Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL7) in the framework of common criteria for computer security certification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Formal verification can be helpful in proving the correctness of systems such as: cryptographic protocols, combinational circuits, digital circuits with internal memory, and software expressed as source code in a programming language.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Prominent examples of verified software systems include the CompCert verified C compiler and the seL4 high-assurance operating system kernel.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The verification of these systems is done by ensuring the existence of a formal proof of a mathematical model of the system.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Model checking involves a systematic and exhaustive exploration of the mathematical model.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Such exploration is possible for finite models, but also for some infinite models, where infinite sets of states can be effectively represented finitely by using abstraction or taking advantage of symmetry.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Usually, this consists of exploring all states and transitions in the model, by using smart and domain-specific abstraction techniques to consider whole groups of states in a single operation and reduce computing time.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Implementation techniques include state space enumeration, symbolic state space enumeration, abstract interpretation, symbolic simulation, abstraction refinement.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The properties to be verified are often described in temporal logics, such as linear temporal logic (LTL), Property Specification Language (PSL), SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA), or computational tree logic (CTL).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Another approach is deductive verification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Formal verification of software programs involves proving that a program satisfies a formal specification of its behavior.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Subareas of formal verification include deductive verification (see above), abstract interpretation, automated theorem proving, type systems, and lightweight formal methods.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] A promising type-based verification approach is dependently typed programming, in which the types of functions include (at least part of) those functions' specifications, and type-checking the code establishes its correctness against those specifications.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Fully featured dependently typed languages support deductive verification as a special case.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Another complementary approach is program derivation, in which efficient code is produced from functional specifications by a series of correctness-preserving steps.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] An example of this approach is the Bird–Meertens formalism, and this approach can be seen as another form of program synthesis.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] These techniques can be *sound*, meaning that the verified properties can be logically deduced from the semantics, or *unsound*, meaning that there is no such guarantee.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] A sound technique yields a result only once it has covered the entire space of possibilities.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] An example of an unsound technique is one that covers only a subset of the possibilities, for instance only integers up to a certain number, and give a "good-enough" result.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Techniques can also be *decidable*, meaning that their algorithmic implementations are guaranteed to terminate with an answer, or undecidable, meaning that they may never terminate.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] By bounding the scope of possibilities, unsound techniques that are decidable might be able to be constructed when no decidable sound techniques are available.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Verification is one aspect of testing a product's fitness for purpose.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Often one refers to the overall checking process as V & V.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The verification process consists of static/structural and dynamic/behavioral aspects.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] E.g., for a software product one can inspect the source code (static) and run against specific test cases (dynamic).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Validation usually can be done only dynamically, i.e., the product is tested by putting it through typical and atypical usages ("Does it satisfactorily meet all use cases?").
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Program repair is performed with respect to an oracle, encompassing the desired functionality of the program which is used for validation of the generated fix.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] A simple example is a test-suite—the input/output pairs specify the functionality of the program.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] A variety of techniques are employed, most notably using satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solvers, and genetic programming, using evolutionary computing to generate and evaluate possible candidates for fixes.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The former method is deterministic, while the latter is randomized.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] For example, the Nopol tool encodes the repair of buggy conditional statements as an SMT instance to determinstically generate patches for if conditions and missing preconditions.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Program repair combines techniques from formal verification and program synthesis.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Fault-localization techniques in formal verification are used to compute program points which might be possible bug-locations, which can be targeted by the synthesis modules.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Repair systems often focus on a small pre-defined class of bugs in order to reduce the search space.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Industrial use is limited owing to the computational cost of existing techniques.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The growth in complexity of designs increases the importance of formal verification techniques in the hardware industry.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] At present, formal verification is used by most or all leading hardware companies, but its use in the software industry is still languishing.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] This could be attributed to the greater need in the hardware industry, where errors have greater commercial significance.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Because of the potential subtle interactions between components, it is increasingly difficult to exercise a realistic set of possibilities by simulation.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Important aspects of hardware design are amenable to automated proof methods, making formal verification easier to introduce and more productive.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] As of 2011, several operating systems have been formally verified: NICTA's Secure Embedded L4 microkernel, sold commercially as seL4 by OK Labs; OSEK/VDX based real-time operating system ORIENTAIS by East China Normal University; Green Hills Software's Integrity operating system; and SYSGO's PikeOS.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] In 2016, a team led by Zhong Shao at Yale developed a formally verified operating system kernel called CertiKOS.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] As of 2017, formal verification has been applied to the design of large computer networks through a mathematical model of the network, and as part of a new network technology category, intent-based networking.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] Network software vendors that offer formal verification solutions include Cisco Forward Networks and Veriflow Systems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The SPARK programming language provides a toolset which enables software development with formal verification and is used in several high-integrity systems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/formal-verification] The CompCert C compiler is a formally verified C compiler implementing the majority of ISO C.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] In computer science, **model checking** or **property checking** is a method for checking whether a finite-state model of a system meets a given specification (also known as correctness).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] This is typically associated with hardware or software systems, where the specification contains liveness requirements (such as avoidance of livelock) as well as safety requirements (such as avoidance of states representing a system crash).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] In order to solve such a problem algorithmically, both the model of the system and its specification are formulated in some precise mathematical language.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] To this end, the problem is formulated as a task in logic, namely to check whether a structure satisfies a given logical formula.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] This general concept applies to many kinds of logic and many kinds of structures.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] A simple model-checking problem consists of verifying whether a formula in the propositional logic is satisfied by a given structure.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Property checking is used for verification when two descriptions are not equivalent.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] During refinement, the specification is complemented with details that are unnecessary in the higher-level specification.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] There is no need to verify the newly introduced properties against the original specification since this is not possible.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Therefore, the strict bi-directional equivalence check is relaxed to a one-way property check.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The implementation or design is regarded as a model of the system, whereas the specifications are properties that the model must satisfy.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] An important class of model-checking methods has been developed for checking models of hardware and software designs where the specification is given by a temporal logic formula.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Pioneering work in temporal logic specification was done by Amir Pnueli, who received the 1996 Turing award for "seminal work introducing temporal logic into computing science".
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Model checking began with the pioneering work of E.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Clarke, Emerson, and Sifakis shared the 2007 Turing Award for their seminal work founding and developing the field of model checking.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Model checking is most often applied to hardware designs.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] For software, because of undecidability (see computability theory) the approach cannot be fully algorithmic, apply to all systems, and always give an answer; in the general case, it may fail to prove or disprove a given property.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] In embedded-systems hardware, it is possible to validate a specification delivered, e.g., by means of UML activity diagrams or control-interpreted Petri nets.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The structure is usually given as a source code description in an industrial hardware description language or a special-purpose language.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Such a program corresponds to a finite-state machine (FSM), i.e., a directed graph consisting of nodes (or vertices) and edges.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] A set of atomic propositions is associated with each node, typically stating which memory elements are one.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The nodes represent states of a system, the edges represent possible transitions that may alter the state, while the atomic propositions represent the basic properties that hold at a point of execution.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Formally, the problem can be stated as follows: given a desired property, expressed as a temporal logic formula p , and a structure M with initial state s , decide if $M,s\models p$ .
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] If M is finite, as it is in hardware, model checking reduces to a graph search.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Instead of enumerating reachable states one at a time, the state space can sometimes be traversed more efficiently by considering large numbers of states at a single step.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] When such state-space traversal is based on representations of a set of states and transition relations as logical formulas, binary decision diagrams (BDD) or other related data structures, the model-checking method is *symbolic*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Historically, the first symbolic methods used BDDs.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] After the success of propositional satisfiability in solving the planning problem in artificial intelligence (see satplan) in 1996, the same approach was generalized to model checking for linear temporal logic (LTL): the planning problem corresponds to model checking for safety properties.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] This method is known as bounded model checking.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The success of Boolean satisfiability solvers in bounded model checking led to the widespread use of satisfiability solvers in symbolic model checking.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] One example of such a system requirement: *Between the time an elevator is called at a floor and the time it opens its doors at that floor, the elevator can arrive at that floor at most twice*.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Here, $\Box$ should be read as "always", $\Diamond$ as "eventually", ${\mathcal {U}}$ as "until" and the other symbols are standard logical symbols, $\lor$ for "or", $\land$ for "and" and $\lnot$ for "not".
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Model-checking tools face a combinatorial blow up of the state-space, commonly known as the state explosion problem, that must be addressed to solve most real-world problems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] There are several approaches to combat this problem.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Bounded model-checking algorithms unroll the FSM for a fixed number of steps, k , and check whether a property violation can occur in k or fewer steps.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] This typically involves encoding the restricted model as an instance of SAT.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The process can be repeated with larger and larger values of k until all possible violations have been ruled out (cf.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Iterative deepening depth-first search).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Abstraction attempts to prove properties of a system by first simplifying it.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] The simplified system usually does not satisfy exactly the same properties as the original one so that a process of refinement may be necessary.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Generally, one requires the abstraction to be *sound* (the properties proved on the abstraction are true of the original system); however, sometimes the abstraction is not *complete* (not all true properties of the original system are true of the abstraction).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] An example of abstraction is to ignore the values of non-Boolean variables and to only consider Boolean variables and the control flow of the program; such an abstraction, though it may appear coarse, may, in fact, be sufficient to prove e.g. properties of mutual exclusion.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Counterexample-guided abstraction refinement (CEGAR) begins checking with a coarse (i.e. imprecise) abstraction and iteratively refines it.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] When a violation (i.e. counterexample) is found, the tool analyzes it for feasibility (i.e., is the violation genuine or the result of an incomplete abstraction?).
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] If the violation is feasible, it is reported to the user.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] If it is not, the proof of infeasibility is used to refine the abstraction and checking begins again.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Model-checking tools were initially developed to reason about the logical correctness of discrete state systems, but have since been extended to deal with real-time and limited forms of hybrid systems.
[src:formal-equivalence-checking/model-checking] Model checking is also studied in the field of computational complexity theory.
